{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":14457,"record_hash":"sha256:35d695024a55d64933ad7638b4a00c2f86b0dafa40aa26ab47cb840bcdd5cbca","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:53:58.376Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/agent-session-capture/future-use-cases.md\n@@\n For this to work later, GitButler needs to capture enough session context into\n GitMeta, move that metadata through Git transport, and expose it on the other\n side in a form that another agent can use. The POC does not serialize, push,\n fetch, or resume a session, but its project-scoped session records should be\n durable enough to make that possible.\n+\n+Expected access pattern:\n+\n+1. fetch or otherwise exchange GitMeta data for the repository\n+2. read `gitbutler:agent-sessions` from the `project` target\n+3. choose a session, either by recency, user selection, or a future explicit\n+   relationship\n+4. read `gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript`\n+5. reconstruct useful context from `content_text`, `event_category`,\n+   `tool_name`, and redacted `source_record`\n+\n+That means the transcript list must be readable without knowing the original\n+machine's file paths, cwd, branch state, or raw provider session id.\n@@\n The POC only captures redacted session records. It does not create web links,\n publish metadata, or attach sessions to pull requests.\n+\n+Expected access pattern:\n+\n+1. start from a pull request, branch, change, or commit\n+2. read its future `gitbutler:agent-sessions` relationship set\n+3. resolve those session keys on the `project` target\n+4. render each session's transcript timeline from the slim envelope fields\n+5. use redacted `source_record` for provenance and later normalization upgrades\n+\n+That means branch/PR metadata should point to sessions, not contain copies of\n+session transcripts.\n@@\n The durable object should therefore be the project-scoped GitButler agent\n session. Branches, commits, changes, and pull requests should later reference\n session keys rather than own the transcript data directly.\n+\n+This is especially important for GitButler because a single worktree may contain\n+multiple active branches at once. An agent can produce edits that the user later\n+splits across several branches, so the capture layer should not guess ownership\n+from the current branch.\n@@\n The first POC should:\n \n - write redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys\n - keep session data on the `project` target by default\n - use a durable session key independent of branches and commits\n - keep source metadata separate from per-record transcript envelopes\n+- keep enough normalized fields to support timeline browsing without reparsing\n+  every provider-specific record\n - avoid storing local paths, cwd values, branches, or raw provider session\n   ids\n - avoid serialization, push, fetch, sync, branch inference, and PR association\n+\n+The POC should not try to solve session merging. A future UX can decide whether\n+multiple provider sessions should be joined into one GitButler-level session.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:53:58.376Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}